		<credit project="CfPBoK@https://slebok.github.io/cfpbok/"/>
		<div class="right"><a href="index.html"><img src="../sle.png" alt="SLE 2012"></a><br><code>sle2012/paper11</code></div>
			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2012</a> paper:</span><br><i>Grammatical Inference in Software Engineering: An Overview of the State of the Art</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/AndrewWStevenson.html">Andrew W. Stevenson</a>, <a href="../profile/JamesRCordy.html">James R. Cordy</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-642-36089-3_12">10.1007/978-3-642-36089-3_12</a></li>
<li>Original shorter version of <a href="../sle2012s/paper03.html"><em>A survey of grammatical inference in software engineering</em></a> (SLE 2012 SI)</li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4g.html"><span class="tagM">T4G: AI-for-SLE</span></a><ul><li> The paper surveys grammar inference (learning grammars from data), which is an AI/ML-style technique applied to SLE tasks.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3a.html"><span class="tagL">T3A: Meta-languages</span></a><ul><li> The inferred artifacts are grammars/language definitions, i.e., meta-language objects central to software language engineering.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5b.html"><span class="tagL">T5B: Language Description Analysis</span></a><ul><li> It is concerned with recovering/analyzing language descriptions (grammars) from programs, traces, or other artifacts.
</li></ul></li></ul>
